Rules of Engagement: Level 1
Time Limit: 60 Minutes.

The Environment: A fresh, running RHEL 9 VM. You are logged in as a regular user who has sudo privileges (or just log in as root).

The Goal: Accuracy over speed.

Log into your VM and run these verification commands.

1. The Privilege Check
For the exam, you need to be able to switch to the root user or use sudo to create users and modify /opt.

Bash

# Check your current user
whoami

# Try to elevate to root
sudo su -
Success: You are prompted for your password and your prompt changes to root@...#.

(Note: Stay as root for the rest of these checks).

2. The OS & Kernel Verification
Just to confirm you are sitting in your new RHEL 10 environment and check which kernel it's running.

Bash

cat /etc/os-release
uname -r
Success: You should see Red Hat Enterprise Linux 10 (or CentOS Stream 10) and a kernel version starting with 6.x.

3. The Network Connection
Task 9 requires you to download a package. Let's make sure your virtual NIC is passing traffic to the outside world.

Bash

# Check if you can resolve and reach DNS
ping -c 4 google.com
Success: You see 4 packets transmitted, 4 received, 0% packet loss.

Failure: If it fails, check your KVM network settings (ensure the VM is attached to the default NAT network) and run nmcli con up "eth0" (or whatever your interface name is via ip a).

4. The Repository Check
Pinging the internet is one thing, but can your package manager actually talk to the Red Hat software repositories?

Bash

# Clear any stale metadata and build a fresh cache
dnf clean all
dnf makecache
Success: It downloads the metadata and says Metadata cache created.

Failure: If it fails with "No repositories enabled" or "Cannot download repomd.xml", your VM might not be registered with Red Hat (via subscription-manager), or if using CentOS Stream, the base repos aren't reachable.

5. The Clean Slate Check
The mock exam asks you to create specific users (intern1) and groups (juniors). Let's ensure they don't already exist from a previous lab.

Bash

id intern1
getent group juniors
Success: The system should return no such user and no output for the group. If they exist, delete them with userdel -r intern1 and groupdel juniors.

You are cleared for takeoff! ✈️
If those 5 checks pass, your RHEL 10 VM is perfectly configured to handle the 60-minute Beginner Mock Exam.


📝 RHCSA Mock Exam: Beginner Level ("Bootcamp")
Task 1: System Reconnaissance

Find your system's current hostname and write it into a new file located at /root/system_info.txt.

Task 2: The Directory Tree

Create a nested directory structure in one command: /opt/training/linux101.

Inside linux101, create an empty file named practice.txt.

Task 3: Basic User Management

Create a new user named intern1.

Set their password to linuxisfun.

Task 4: Group Assignment

Create a new group named juniors.

Add the user intern1 to the juniors group.

Task 5: Ownership and Permissions

Change the group ownership of the directory /opt/training/linux101 to the juniors group.

Change the permissions on /opt/training/linux101 so that the Owner and Group have Read, Write, and Execute (rwx) access, but Others have zero access (---).

Task 6: Text Manipulation

Add the sentence "I am learning Red Hat" to the file /opt/training/linux101/practice.txt. (Do this from the command line, do not open a text editor like vim or nano).

Task 7: Searching for Text (Grep)

Search the file /etc/services for the exact word ssh.

Save only the lines that match into a new file at /root/ssh_port.txt.

Task 8: Archiving and Compression (Tar)

Create a gzip-compressed archive of the entire /opt/training directory.

Save the archive as /root/training_backup.tar.gz.

Task 9: Package Management

Using the command line, install the package tmux.

(Note: Your VM needs internet access to reach the default Red Hat or CentOS Stream repositories).

Task 10: Basic Service Management

The SSH service is critical. Verify its current status.

Ensure the service named sshd is enabled to start automatically every time the server boots.
